rves as the Regimental S 2 Captain  she is a member of the Powerlifting Team  and she is a regular in our fitness facilities  She will be commissioned in the U S  Army upon graduation  Cadet Tyler Lighton  15 Tyler has maintained academic stars his entire cadetship  and has done so while competing as a Division 1 NCAA baseball player  An English Major from Chesapeake  Virginia  he is a member of Sigma Tau Delta honor society  He is currently interning with the VMI Foundation under a new program created in collaboration with the Department of English  Rhetoric  and Humanistic Studies  Many of you probably read his first published piece in the October edition of the Institute Report  Your generosity has helped Tyler to excel on the field and in the classroom  The private resources that allow VMI to maintain a 11 1 cadet to faculty ratio also allows cadets like Tyler direct access to what I think are some of the best instructor  educators in the nation  LTC Tim Moore  97 Although he may not have known it then  donor support played a major role in causing LTC Moore to leave a successful engineering career to return to his alma mater to teach in 2010  Tim recognized at that time the effect that faculty can have on cadets  and he was willing to make the  career change  because of people in this room who have invested in faculty support and academic innovation  With your support  Tim was able to create the  Field to Forum  program  an interdisciplinary program that helps cadets bridge the gap between the classroom and the world of practice as professional engineers  He also created the VMI Clean Energy and Air Resources Program  known as CLEAR  that is noted for developing sustainable bio fuels  The CLEAR Program   with your generous contributions for academic research   gives cadets opportunities to study and create clean burning bio fuels from soybeans  And Tim didn t stop there   he also founded the service group  Keydets Without Borders  Under this program  dozens of c